<li id="cite_note-Bowlby_58-20">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Bowlby_58_20-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Bowlby_58_20-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Bowlby_58_20-2" title=""><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Bowlby_58_20-3" title=""><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Bowlby_58_20-4" title=""><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Bowlby_58_20-5" title=""><sup><i><b>f</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Bowlby_58_20-6" title=""><sup><i><b>g</b></i></sup></a> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFBowlby_J1958">Bowlby J (1958). "The nature of the child's tie to his mother". <i>International Journal of Psychoanalysis</i> <b>39</b> (5): 350–73. <a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/13610508" class="external" title="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/13610508">PMID 13610508</a>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=The+nature+of+the+child%27s+tie+to+his+mother&amp;rft.jtitle=International+Journal+of+Psychoanalysis&amp;rft.aulast=Bowlby+J&amp;rft.au=Bowlby+J&amp;rft.date=1958&amp;rft.volume=39&amp;rft.issue=5&amp;rft.pages=350%E2%80%9373&amp;rft_id=info:pmid/13610508&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Attachment_theory"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-21"><b><a href="#cite_ref-21" title="">^</a></b> Bowlby (1969) 2nd ed. p. 309.</li>
<li id="cite_note-Main-22"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Main_22-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFMain_M1999">Main M (1999). "Epilogue:Attachment Theory:Eighteen Points with Suggestions for Future Studies". in Cassidy J, Shaver PR. <i>Handbook of Attachment: Theory, Research and Clinical Applications</i>. New York: Guilford press. pp.&#160;845–887. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/1572300876" class="internal">ISBN 1-57230-087-6</a>.  "although there is general agreement that an infant or adult will have only a few attachment figures at most, many attachment theorists and researchers believe that infants form 'attachment hierarchies' in which some figures are primary, others secondary and so on. This position can be presented in a stronger form, in which a particular figure is believed continually to take top place ("monotropy")...questions surrounding monotropy and attachment hierarchies remain unsettled".</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Epilogue%3AAttachment+Theory%3AEighteen+Points+with+Suggestions+for+Future+Studies&amp;rft.atitle=Handbook+of+Attachment%3A+Theory%2C+Research+and+Clinical+Applications&amp;rft.aulast=Main+M&amp;rft.au=Main+M&amp;rft.date=1999&amp;rft.pages=pp.%26nbsp%3B845%E2%80%93887&amp;rft.place=New+York&amp;rft.pub=Guilford+press&amp;rft.isbn=1-57230-087-6&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Attachment_theory"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
